<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I memorized the spell gave him back the spell book  and then cast it.  A rift in the air opened and time and space folded as we walked through it.  We stood at the Druid Rings in the far corner of Dreadlands in Kunark. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp  Farvak was pleased &quot;That sure beats the boats.  Now for our passage to the Overthere and the docks.&quot;  I stood where I was eyes lowered  as Farvak said &quot;Well now how do you think is the best way to go Kat?&quot;   I answered &quot;I will need my spell book again. I need to cast Spirit of Wolf, See Invisible, Levitate and Superior Camouflage on all of us for the safest travel&quot;  He grinned and gave a nod to Iszabelle, as he handed me the spell book again.  Sitting and memorizing the needed spells I felt like such a traitor to my Family.  <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I swore that somehow I would die if I couldn't help the Bronze Dragons to defeat these horrid Plague Bringers.  I would turn my Druid Skills against them as best I could.  But for now I would learn all I could of their plans.  I thought of Kygero and her friend sitting outside of Farvak's home waiting for me to come out of the house that morning.  What had they thought of Farvak's wife in the barn that night.  Had they seen Farvak with my spell book.  <br>
<br>
        I hoped that they would remain safely hidden.  I knew that Farvak would become even more obsessed with me as my Druid Powers would give him more power in the Plague Bringers.  He was an ego thinking itself a God.  <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I returned the spell book once again to Farvak, proceeded to cast the necessary spells.  Once done I guided them through the dangers of the Dreadlands to the tunnel through to the Frontier Mountains then on to the land known as the Overthere.  I lead them to the Dock area.  I had never been inside, it had been known as a death trap for any one who served the Truth and Light of Tunare.  Farvak lead me in as I hesitated.  <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp A rush of guards came at us then stopped as they saw Iszabelle and Farvak with me chained to him.  A look of satisfaction came over both of them as they walked through to a building.  I stood by Iszabelle as Farvak went to gain the owners key to the place.  Upon returning he opened the door and said &quot;This will do for our headquarters here&quot;  Iszabelle nodded as we entered.  She went upstairs to check out the rooms there.  Farvak eyes gleamed at me and his fingers once again traced the scratches on his face.  He looked as though he were in a moment of ecstasy.  He leaned over and whispered &quot;Tonight&quot;.  <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Well you did that so well Kat that we are going to have you do it again&quot;  Iszabelle said returning.   &quot;Farvak have her take you to Lavastorm then on to Neriak to pick up and teleport  those that are waiting for us there.  This will turn out much better than I had planned.   You have done well Farvak, but keep her under control at all times&quot; she threatened.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Farvak made me do this once more that day.  Brining those who served Iszabelle and her Dark Lord.   I was met in Neriak with distaste which did not change and it was Farvak who received the congratulatory pats on the back when they reached the Docks safely and so quickly.  <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Iszabelle too was pleased.  Her personal servant taking charge  and things in the building were taking shape to her desires while we were gone.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The group entered the building and a round of Congradtuations to Iszabelle where said.  &quot;You have a good man in Farvak who would have thought to capture one of our enemies Druids for our use&quot;   Farvak strutting with pride dragging me behind him.  He ordered me taken to his room &quot;Feed her as well, but chain her to the wall and make sure there is someone there to watch her now&quot;<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp   I was lead away and up the stairs remembering his whispered words &quot;Tonight&quot;. I knew it was no use to keep my temper under control with the potions he had at his disposal.  Last night I may not have remembered much, but what I did remember was my rage. Rage and hate pouring out onto him and his delight that it had.  I was ashamed, I thought that I had learned to let it go, to grow beyond all of that hate.  Now here it was again rearing it's ugly head to serve him, of all people.  <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I again fell into prayer to Mother Tunare and into meditation.  I knew what was going to happen later tonight and I needed her strength to help me through it.<br>
